@NODE NEW "What's new with PSMail V1.2..."

Firstly, to save any confusion, this version of PSMail relies very heavily
on GhostScript's ability to access the host computer's file system - so there's
no way on earth you'll get this to work directly with a PostScript printer.
(GhostScript's pswrite device might help you out if you really need to use
a PostScript printer, but this is not an ideal solution).

@{b}Version 1.2@{ub}
A requester now appears while the mails are being printed, which provides you
with the ability to cancel the printout.  Thanks to Mike Carter for suggesting
this.
You will have problems with this requester if your t: assign happens to be
on a filesystem which doesn't support file notification.  Its normal location
is ram:t, which should be fine, as should FastFileSystem under KickStart 3 or
better.

Most of the text strings used during the printing process are now collected
towards the top of the Prolog1.2.ps file, which should make life a lot easier
for those who want to translate it into other languages.

@{b}Version 1.1@{ub}
Version 1.1 of PSMail provides rudimentary support for attachments.
Files of type text/plain will be printed with the body of the mail, and
all other types will be summarised with filename, type and size.

Several bugs in the PostScript code have been fixed - mostly in the word
wrapping code.

A bug caused all but page one from a mail to be printed too low on the page.
Thanks to Guillaume Ubbelohde and Jens Thos for pointing this out.

A mechanism has been added for choosing which mail-headers are printed.
Thanks to Jens Thos again for suggesting this.

Another bug which caused problems with encrypted and compressed mail folders
has been fixed - though it is dependent on YAM's naming of temporary files,
so might well need updating for future versions of YAM.

@ENDNODE


@NODE INSTALLATION "Installing and Customising PSMail..."
@{b}Installing@{ub}

To install PSMail, just drag the PSMail drawer into the YAM:Rexx directory.
Now start YAM and on the Config/REXX page choose a slot for the script,
and set its filename to REXX/PSMail/GSMail.yam

Make sure that the `Wait for termination' gadget is NOT selected, and save
your prefs.

Out of the box, PSMail assumes that you're using TurboPrint, and a version
of GhostScript with the turboprint device compiled in.  If this is not the
case you will need to perform one last step before you can use the scripts;
open the print.script file in a text editor, and change the GhostScript:gs
line to suit your model of printer.  Hints are provided in the file.

A new feature for this version is the ability to choose the headers which
will be printed at the top of the mail.
To do this you will need to edit the Prolog1.2.ps file.  Instructions can
be found there.  Unfortunately, when there are several headers of the same
type (as is usually the case with the Received: headers), only the last one
will be printed.  Fixing this problem will require major changes to PSMail's
operation, so it's unlikely to be done for a while!

Many of the strings used within PSMail are now collected near the top of
the file, which should make life easier for those who want to translate it
into other languages.

@ENDNODE


@NODE REQUIREMENTS "What is needed to use PSMail..."
@{b}You need the following hardware and software to make use of PSMail:@{ub}

» An Amiga

» A printer

» YAM - the Amiga's best EMail Client.

» ARexx - RexxMast should be running when you use PSMail...

» @{"GhostScript" link GHOSTSCRIPT}.  This version definitely needs GhostScript!

@{b}Not strictly speaking required, but highly recommended:@{ub}

» TurboPrint 7

» The version of GhostScript from IrseeSoft's website, www.irseesoft.com


@ENDNODE


@NODE GHOSTSCRIPT "About GhostScript..."
@{b}What is GhostScript?@{ub}
GhostScript is pretty much a complete PostScript Level 2 interpreter.
It is widely used in the LINUX/UNIX world, where many programs which
want to produce decent printed output do so through PostScript.

@{b}So what's PostScript then?@{ub}
PostScript is a page description language developed by (and a trademark
of) Adobe Systems.  Instead of describing a printed page as an array of
dots to be produced by a print head, PostScript stores a page as a
high-level description of lines, words, fonts and images.  PostScript
is in fact a complete and powerful programming language, and when
it's interpreted on a computer (rather than inside a printer) all kinds
of clever tricks are possible; it is quite possible for a GhostScript program
to read a text file from disk and flush-justify it into multiple columns,
placing PCX, JPEG and EPS images as it goes.  PSMail uses postscript code
to perform word-wrapping.  The language itself is pretty confusing for
beginners though, so don't delete your DTP package just yet!

@{b}Why would I need GhostScript?@{ub}
Do you need to print PostScript files?  If so, GhostScript is the best
way to do so on the Amiga - unless of course you have a printer which
is PostScript-capable.  GhostScript, in combination with TurboPrint
can be used to coax 24-bit printouts out of ProPage 4, PageStream 2.2
and many other older program.

Do you need to print PDF files?  Yes, GhostScript can handle those too.

Do you need to CREATE PDF files?  GhostScript can even make a decent
stab at this task!

Finally, do you want to print decent-looking EMails from YAM?

If the answer to any of these questions is yes, you need GhostScript.

@{b}OK, where can I get it?@{ub}
Do you have TurboPrint 7?  If so, you've already got it - though you
may not have installed it yet.  The version which comes with TP7 is
quite old, but perfectly usable - there is a newer version available
for free download on IrseeSoft's website, (www.irseesoft.com) which
is well worth getting.  For legal reasons the newer version couldn't
be bundled with TurboPrint.

It is also available on Aminet, in the gfx/show directory.  This version
can't print through turboprint though.  If you have TurboPrint get the
version from IrseeSoft's site.

Finally, check magazine cover CDs - It has made it more than once onto
CU-Amiga's and Amiga Format's CDs.  The version on Aminet (GS5.10) can be
found on AFCD35 in the -in_the_Mag-/PDF directory.

If you're going to download from Aminet...

You need these:
  gfx/show     GS510-data.lha 326K  73 GS5.10 Data-init-config files
  gfx/show GS510-stdfonts.lha 1.5M  73 GS5.10 fonts-std files
  text/dtp   GS510FontMap.lha   5K  62 GS5.10's missing fontmap file

One of the following, depending on your processor:
  gfx/show      GS510_020.lha 537K  73 GS5.10-4-020-030-EC040-Amigas
  gfx/show   GS510_020fpu.lha 518K  73 GS5.10-4-020fpu-030fpu-Amigas
  gfx/show   GS510_040fpu.lha 520K  73 GS5.10-4-040fpu-Amigas

Optional - but probably worth getting:
  text/dtp  GS510-Install.lha  15K  32 GS5.10-Installation-Routine (V1.02)
  gfx/show GS510-fontsoth.lha 798K  73 GS5.10 fonts-other files

If you're totally new to GhostScript, click @{"here" link GSTUTORIAL} for a brief
tutorial.

@ENDNODE


@NODE INTRO "Introduction..."

If you've used YAM for any length of time you'll probably realise that
it is one of the best EMail programs on any platform, but if you've ever
tried printing mails, you probably took one look at the result and said
"YUK"!  If you share my dislike of mono-spaced printer fonts, then PSMail
is for you.

PSMail is a collection of scripts (two written in ARexx, two in AmigaDOS
and one PostScript `prolog') plus a couple of executables, which together
will enable YAM to produce decent looking printed E-Mails

PSMail 1.1 adds support for attachments and fixes a couple of bugs in the
PostScript prolog.

PSMail 1.2 adds a status/cancel requester, and makes life a little easier
for translators.

@ENDNODE


