@NODE GSTUTORIAL "A brief tutorial on using GhostScript!"
N.B. the following tutorial assumes that you are comfortable with
using the shell, creating directories and assigns, and editing files.

If you are uncomfortable with any of these topics, keep your Amiga's
manual close to hand while you follow these instructions!

@{b}Setting up GhostScript@{ub}

If you've not used GhostScript before, it can be quite an intimidating
program to begin with.

Once you've collected and unpacked the GS5.10 archives, you will need to
make a GhostScript drawer on your harddisk.  Make an assign to this
drawer, i.e. Assign GhostScript: wherever_the_drawer_is
and copy the files into it, using the following directory structure:

GhostScript:
  GS
        The main executable.  You only need the particular executable
        compiled for your processor, probably named something like GS020,
        but you should rename it to GS.

GhostScript:Data (Unless you're using the older GhostScript 4.03 from the
                  TurboPrint 7 disks, in which case just use GhostScript:)
  GS_#?.ps
        These are PostScript utility files needed by GhostScript itself.
        The PostScript language is powerful enough that a fair number
        of GhostScript's experimental functions are in these files!

  PDF_#?.ps
        These are utility files required to use GhostScript's PDF support.

  <everything_else>.ps
        These are just example PostScript files - but well worth reading
        if you want to learn more about the language.

  #?.upp
        These are driver definitions for GhostScript's UniPrint driver.
        More on this later.

GhostScript:Fonts
  #?.pfa, #?.pfm, #?.pfb, #?.gsf, #?.afm
        These are the various fonts found in the StdFonts and FontsOther
        archives.
  FontMap
        This file (which was cleverly left out of the Aminet GhostScript
        archives) is used to map the fonts' real names to the 8 character
        filenames which are provided for MS-DOS (Yak!) support.
        This is also used to handle font aliases - for example, Palatino
        is mapped to URW-Palladio, while Helvetica gets mapped to
        Nimbus-Sans.  Don't worry if you haven't got the FontMap file -
        it can be found in the Text/DTP directory of Aminet, or in the
        Goodies archive.

Once all the files are installed correctly, you are ready to try it out!

Open a shell window, and type the following:

stack 100000
cd GhostScript
GS -sDEVICE=amiga_custom -r80x80

The stack command is needed because GhostScript, being a UNIX port, uses
up LOADS of stack space.  After a 20 or 30 seconds or disk activity,
GhostScript will open a custom screen behind the workbench, containing
a blank page.  The shell window should now be showing a GS> prompt.
If so, try typing the following:

/Palatino findfont 40 scalefont setfont
10 700 moveto (Hello World!) show
showpage

If everything is setup correctly, the blank page will now have the words
Hello World printed somewhere near the top, in 40 point Palatino.
The final showpage command was responsible for bringing the custom screen
to the front.  Use Amiga-m to get back to the shell window, and press
return, as prompted.  This will clear the page.  If GhostScript is being
used with a printer instead of the screen, the showpage command will
actually start up the printer.

To quit GhostScript, just go back to the shell window, press <return> to
clear the ShowPage message, and type Quit.

@{B}Devices@{ub}

GhostScript has a number of built in drivers for various devices.  In the
example above we used the amiga_custom device.  There is also an
amiga_printer device - but it doesn't work properly for me.  You could try
it; you may have more luck.  The version which comes with TP7 and the version
available for download from IrseeSoft's site have a new device named
turboprint which works beautifully.

There are also a number of built-in drivers for various printers, including
(early) Epson Stylus Color models, the Canon BJ series, and others.  A list
of devices can be obtained by typing gs -h
The devices built into the version on IrseeSoft's site are:
   amiga amiga_printer amiga_ilbm amiga_custom turboprint stcolor epsonc
   epson eps9mid eps9high ibmpro deskjet djet500 laserjet ljetplus ljet2p
   ljet3 ljet4 cdeskjet cdjcolor cdjmono cdj550 pj pjxl pjxl300 uniprint
   bj10e bj200 bjc600 bjc800 faxg3 faxg32d faxg4 pcxmono pcxgray pcx16
   pcx256 pcx24b pcxcmyk pbm pbmraw pgm pgmraw pgnm pgnmraw pnm pnmraw ppm
   ppmraw tiffcrle tiffg3 tiffg32d tiffg4 tifflzw tiffpack tiff12nc tiff24nc
   psmono psgray bit bitrgb bitcmyk pngmono pnggray png16 png256 png16m jpeg
   jpeggray pdfwrite pswrite epswrite pxlmono pxlcolor nullpage

Quite a list.  Apart from the Amiga-specific drivers, all the others expect
to create a file which will subsequently be sent somewhere, so to use
GhostScript with my BJC250 (in b/w mode), I type:

GS -sDEVICE=bj200 -sOutputFile=par:

(Please note, GhostScript comes from the UNIX world, where pretty much
EVERYTHING is case-sensitive, so -sDevice won't work; the lines must be
typed in EXACTLY as they appear here!)

As a final example, using the UniPrint driver for Epson Stylus Color 600:

gs -sOutputFile=par: @stc600p.upp

The stc600p.upp file is actually nothing more than a collection of command-line
arguments, in a text file.  Any text file containing command-line arguments
can be used the same way (by putting an @ sign before its name).  The .upp
files for GhostScript 5.10 can be found in the goodies archive provided with
this package, since I think they were forgotten from the Aminet distribution.

@{b}Paper size@{ub}

GhostScript by default uses a US Letter paper size.  If you want to change this
to A4, follow these steps:
edit the GhostScript:Data/gs_init.ps file, and find the line which
starts with:
% (a4) /PAPERSIZE where
The % sign comments out everything else on the line, so to select A4 paper
as the default, you simply need to remove the %, save the file, and restart
GhostScript.

@ENDNODE


@NODE Files "What's in the archive..."

@{b}The PSMail directory should contain the following files:@{ub}

PSMail.guide - You're reading this right now.

GSMail.yam   - The ARexx script.

Prolog1.2.ps - PostScript support routines.

Print.script - AmigaDOS script - prints and then delete the PostScript file.

Wait.script  - AmigaDOS script - Waits for PostScript files from previous print
               jobs to be deleted.

PSMailPrep   - A little executable which sets up an environment variable with
               a break command which is used later if the user wants to cancel.

PSMailReq    - An executable which brings up the cancel requester.  It sets up
               a file notification, so the PostScript code can update the
               status line by writing to a file.  When everything is finished,
               the Print.script deletes the file, which brings down the
               requester.

Goodies.lha  - A collection of files which were missing from the version of
               Ghostscript on AFCD35 and, I think, from the Aminet version too.
               (They can be found in the source archive, but that's more than
               3 meg in size!)

@ENDNODE

